            <h2>GEO Principles</h2>
            <p>Effective GEO is built on several key principles:</p>
            <ul class="content-list">
                <li><strong>Factual Accuracy:</strong> AI systems prefer information that aligns with consensus sources and can be verified</li>
                <li><strong>Clarity:</strong> Content that is clearly written and unambiguous is more likely to be referenced</li>
                <li><strong>Authority:</strong> Established brands and credible sources are preferred in AI recommendations</li>
                <li><strong>Uniqueness:</strong> Original information and perspectives that aren't available elsewhere</li>
                <li><strong>Completeness:</strong> Comprehensive coverage of topics that addresses full user intent</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

<!-- GEO vs AEO Section -->
<section class="content-section alt-bg">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="content-block">
            <h2>GEO vs AEO</h2>
            <p>While related, GEO and <a href="/aeo">AEO (Answer Engine Optimisation)</a> address different aspects of AI-influenced search:</p>
            <ul class="content-list">
                <li><strong>AEO</strong> focuses on appearing in featured snippets and direct answers within traditional search results</li>
                <li><strong>GEO</strong> focuses on being referenced by generative AI systems that create synthesised responses</li>
            </ul>
            <p>AEO optimises for extraction—having content pulled into answer boxes. GEO optimises for reference—being a source that AI systems draw upon when generating responses.</p>
            <p>Both disciplines share foundational elements: clear structure, accurate information, and authoritative positioning. Effective strategy typically addresses both.</p>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

